 persuasively illuminated in new ways.The book explores an eclectic range of TV fictions, dramatic and comedic. Contributors from diverse perspectives come together to expand and enrich the kind of close analysis most commonly found in television aesthetics. Sustained, detailed programme analyses are sensitively framed within historical, technological, institutional, cultural, creative and art-historical contexts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aTelevision broadcasting. 0aTelevision. 4aFilm and Media Studies 2021. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Television / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  aTV drama.  aTV evaluation.  aTV series.  aTV substance.  ainterpretation.  astylistic criticism.  asubstance and style.  atelevision aesthetics.  atelevision moments.  atelevision style.1 aAudissino, Emilio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBignell, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBignell, Jonathan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCardwell, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCardwell, Sarah, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCassidy, Gary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClark, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDonaldson, Lucy Fife, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDonaldson, Lucy Fife, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGarcía, Alberto N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHudelet, Ariane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWatts, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWolthuis, Josette, econtributor.